snippet.textDisplay:
Whole story summarized! 

Basically its celebrating Marvi, a female from the famous tale of shah abdul Latif bhittai. Marvi was daughter of poor and was taken by a prince Umar. He asked her to marry him, offered her all the golds and wealth. But marvi denied everything and demaded to return back. Bhittai writes, Marvi says "the threads on my hands are more precious than your whole gold combined". After a long time, when Umar saw her love for her family and place, he allowed her. The peacock 🦚 portrays Marvi coming back and the dance shows celebrations by her poor family members. 

This courage of marvi is still celebrated in Sindh as said (Falsafo Zindagi khe dino thai....)

Umar did not do any force with marvi during her stay at palace, thats the beauty of Sindhi Folk♥️

snippet.textDisplay: This song is about Umar Marvi folktale from Sindh, Pakistan about a village girl Marvi, who resists the overtures of a powerful King the then-ruler of Amarkot, Umar Soomro, who wanted to marry her because of her beauty. Upon her refusal, she was imprisoned in the historic Amarkot Fort for several years. Then she was victorious and returned to her village, and the village is welcoming her. And the new artists or underdogs are relating themselves with her.
